T1  - Editing the 2004 AMJ Best Article Award Winner
AU  - Bergh, Donald D.
Y1  - 2006/04/01
PY  - 2006
DA  - 2006/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2006.20786048
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2006.20786048
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 197
EP  - 202
VL  - 49
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The author discusses his experience serving as the action editor for a three-person panel that reviewed an academic paper submitted for publication. Opinions varied among the reviewers as to the paper's merit, and after a revised manuscript was submitted one of the editors thought the paper had deteriorated in quality. This same reviewer still had reservations after a third edition arrived, but the author decided they were not strong enough to prevent him from conditionally accepting the manuscript for publication. The experience convinced him that papers benefit considerably from peer review, and from authors' willingness to honestly address reviewers' concerns.
AB  - The author discusses his experience serving as the action editor for a three-person panel that reviewed an academic paper submitted for publication. Opinions varied among the reviewers as to the paper's merit, and after a revised manuscript was submitted one of the editors thought the paper had deteriorated in quality. This same reviewer still had reservations after a third edition arrived, but the author decided they were not strong enough to prevent him from conditionally accepting the manuscript for publication. The experience convinced him that papers benefit considerably from peer review, and from authors' willingness to honestly address reviewers' concerns.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2006.20786048
