TY  - JOUR
T1  - Justice and Leader-Member Exchange: The Moderating Role of Organizational Culture
AU  - Erdogan, Berrin
AU  - Liden, Robert C.
AU  - Kraimer, Maria L.
Y1  - 2006/04/01
PY  - 2006
DA  - 2006/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2006.20786086
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2006.20786086
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 395
EP  - 406
VL  - 49
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We hypothesized that organizational culture moderates the relationship between justice perceptions and leader-member exchange (LMX). In a sample of 516 teachers from 30 high schools in Turkey, we found that one dimension of culture from the Organizational Culture Profile, respect for people, strengthened the relationship between interactional justice and LMX, and another dimension, team orientation, weakened that relationship. Furthermore, aggressiveness strengthened, whereas team orientation weakened, the relationship between distributive justice and LMX. Finally, we found that in team-oriented schools, LMX was higher.
AB  - We hypothesized that organizational culture moderates the relationship between justice perceptions and leader-member exchange (LMX). In a sample of 516 teachers from 30 high schools in Turkey, we found that one dimension of culture from the Organizational Culture Profile, respect for people, strengthened the relationship between interactional justice and LMX, and another dimension, team orientation, weakened that relationship. Furthermore, aggressiveness strengthened, whereas team orientation weakened, the relationship between distributive justice and LMX. Finally, we found that in team-oriented schools, LMX was higher.
