T1  - Constructing Professional Identity: The Role of Work and Identity Learning Cycles in the Customization of Identity Among Medical Residents
AU  - Pratt, Michael G.
AU  - Rockmann, Kevin W.
AU  - Kaufmann, Jeffrey B.
Y1  - 2006/04/01
PY  - 2006
DA  - 2006/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2006.20786060
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2006.20786060
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 235
EP  - 262
VL  - 49
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Through a six-year qualitative study of medical residents, we build theory about professional identity construction. We found that identity construction was triggered by work-identity integrity violations: an experienced mismatch between what physicians did and who they were. These violations were resolved through identity customization processes (enriching, patching, or splinting), which were part of interrelated identity and work learning cycles. Implications of our findings (e.g., for member identification) for both theory and practice are discussed.
AB  - Through a six-year qualitative study of medical residents, we build theory about professional identity construction. We found that identity construction was triggered by work-identity integrity violations: an experienced mismatch between what physicians did and who they were. These violations were resolved through identity customization processes (enriching, patching, or splinting), which were part of interrelated identity and work learning cycles. Implications of our findings (e.g., for member identification) for both theory and practice are discussed.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2006.20786060
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amj.2006.20786060
